Azure provides several load-balancing services, each operating at a different layer of the network stack. Azure Load Balancer operates at Layer 4 using T-C-P and U-D-P, distributing traffic across V-M instances within a region at network speed. Application Gateway operates at Layer 7 over H-T-T-P and H-T-T-P-S, providing intelligent routing, S-S-L termination, and a Web Application Firewall within a single region. Azure Front Door operates at Layer 7 globally across the Microsoft edge network, combining a C-D-N with cross-region load balancing and a global W-A-F. Azure Traffic Manager operates at the D-N-S layer, routing clients to different regional endpoints based on a policy without proxying the traffic. This topic focuses on the two most commonly used services: Azure Load Balancer and Application Gateway.

Let us start with Azure Load Balancer.

Azure Load Balancer is a Layer 4 T-C-P and U-D-P load balancer that distributes inbound traffic across healthy backend instances using a five-tuple hash. It operates at network speed with no T-L-S termination and no awareness of H-T-T-P content. It is the Azure equivalent of A-W-S Network Load Balancer.

There are two S-K-Us. The Standard S-K-U supports backend pools of up to 1,000 instances, H-T-T-P-S health probes, availability zone redundancy, outbound rules, multiple frontends, H-A ports, and a 99.99% S-L-A. The Basic S-K-U is limited, does not support availability zones, and is being retired. Always use Standard for new deployments.

An Azure Load Balancer has five core components. The frontend I-P configuration is the public or private I-P address that clients connect to. The backend pool is the set of V-Ms or V-M-S-S instances that receive traffic. The health probe is a periodic H-T-T-P, H-T-T-P-S, or T-C-P check — instances that fail the probe are removed from rotation. The load-balancing rule maps a frontend I-P and port to a backend pool and port using the distribution algorithm. And inbound N-A-T rules map a specific frontend port directly to a specific backend V-M — used for R-D-P or S-S-H access to individual instances.

The default distribution algorithm is the five-tuple hash, which considers source I-P, source port, destination I-P, destination port, and protocol. The same five-tuple always maps to the same backend instance. You can adjust session persistence using two-tuple mode — source I-P and destination I-P — which pins all connections from the same client I-P to the same backend. Or three-tuple mode adds the protocol as well.

A Public Load Balancer has a public I-P on the frontend and distributes inbound internet traffic to V-Ms. An Internal Load Balancer, also called I-L-B, has a private I-P from a V-Net subnet on the frontend and is used for traffic between tiers — for example routing from web servers to application servers.

H-A Ports is a special configuration available on internal Standard Load Balancers. When you set the protocol to All and the port to zero, the load balancer forwards all T-C-P and U-D-P traffic on all ports simultaneously to the backend pool. This is specifically designed for load-balancing Network Virtual Appliances such as firewalls in an active-active pair, where all flows regardless of port must be distributed.

The Standard Load Balancer also supports outbound rules, which give you explicit control over how backend pool instances reach the internet via S-N-A-T. You specify the number of S-N-A-T ports per instance to prevent port exhaustion. A Cross-Region Load Balancer sits in front of regional Standard Load Balancers, providing a single global I-P and routing traffic to the closest healthy region.

Now let us look at Application Gateway.

Azure Application Gateway is a Layer 7 H-T-T-P and H-T-T-P-S load balancer and application delivery controller. Because it understands H-T-T-P, it can route based on U-R-L path, hostname, or headers, terminate T-L-S, rewrite H-T-T-P headers, and apply a Web Application Firewall. It is the Azure equivalent of A-W-S Application Load Balancer combined with A-W-S W-A-F.

There are two S-K-Us, both version 2. Standard v2 provides autoscaling and zone support without a W-A-F. W-A-F v2 adds an integrated Web Application Firewall. Version 1 S-K-Us are retired — always use v2.

Application Gateway has seven key components. The frontend I-P is the public or private I-P clients connect to. The listener sits on the frontend I-P and port and accepts incoming connections — a basic listener handles one site, while a multi-site listener routes based on the H-T-T-P hostname header so multiple domains can share a single Application Gateway. The request routing rule maps a listener to a backend pool and H-T-T-P settings — it can be basic, routing all traffic from a listener to one pool, or path-based, routing different U-R-L paths to different pools. The backend pool contains the destinations — V-Ms, V-M-S-S, App Service, or I-P addresses and fully qualified domain names. H-T-T-P settings define the backend protocol, port, cookie-based session affinity, connection draining, and request timeout. The health probe checks backend instances and removes unhealthy ones. And rewrite rules modify H-T-T-P request or response headers and U-R-Ls before forwarding.

Path-based routing is one of Application Gateway's most useful features. For example, you can route requests for slash images slash star to an image server backend pool, requests for slash api slash star to an A-P-I backend pool, and everything else to the main web server pool — all handled by a single Application Gateway.

Multi-site routing allows multiple hostnames on the same Application Gateway. A listener for app1 dot contoso dot com sends traffic to one backend pool, while a listener for app2 dot contoso dot com sends traffic to a different pool.

For T-L-S, Application Gateway supports S-S-L termination where it decrypts T-L-S and the backend receives plain H-T-T-P. It also supports end-to-end S-S-L where it decrypts, inspects, and then re-encrypts the traffic before forwarding to the backend. Certificates can be stored in Azure Key Vault — the recommended approach — with automatic rotation when the certificate is renewed.

The W-A-F v2 S-K-U includes an integrated Web Application Firewall based on the O-W-A-S-P Core Rule Set. It protects against S-Q-L injection, cross-site scripting, command injection, H-T-T-P protocol violations, and known common vulnerabilities. The W-A-F operates in either Detection mode — which logs violations without blocking, used for tuning — or Prevention mode, which actively blocks malicious requests. W-A-F policies can be attached globally at the Application Gateway level or per listener for per-site policies. You can add custom rules and exclusions to reduce false positives.

The v2 S-K-U scales automatically from a minimum of zero instances up to 125 capacity units based on traffic load. You can set a minimum instance count to keep pre-warmed instances and avoid latency on the first requests after a period of low traffic.

Now let us briefly cover Azure Front Door and Traffic Manager.

Azure Front Door is a global Layer 7 load balancer, C-D-N, and W-A-F operating across more than 150 Points of Presence on the Microsoft edge network. When a user makes a request, it hits the nearest Front Door P-o-P via anycast routing, which terminates T-L-S and then routes the request to the best origin — your backend in the lowest-latency healthy Azure region. Front Door supports latency-based routing, weighted routing for canary deployments, priority-based failover, and session affinity. It also caches content at the edge, reducing origin load. Use Front Door when you need global H-T-T-P load balancing, a C-D-N, or a global W-A-F.

Azure Traffic Manager is a D-N-S-based global router. It does not proxy traffic. Instead, when a client makes a D-N-S query, Traffic Manager returns the address of the best endpoint based on a routing policy. The client then connects directly to that endpoint. This means Traffic Manager works with any protocol, not just H-T-T-P. Routing methods include Performance for routing to the lowest-latency endpoint, Weighted for distributing traffic by proportion, Priority for active-passive failover, Geographic for routing based on the client's location for data residency compliance, and Subnet for routing based on the client I-P range. The main limitation of Traffic Manager compared to Front Door is that failover speed is limited by D-N-S T-T-L — typically 60 to 300 seconds — whereas Front Door detects failures at the connection level.

To choose the right service, start by asking whether traffic is H-T-T-P or H-T-T-P-S. If not, use Azure Load Balancer. If yes, ask whether the scope is global or multi-region — if so, use Front Door for H-T-T-P or Traffic Manager for any protocol. For a single region, ask whether you need W-A-F, U-R-L routing, or S-S-L termination — if yes, use Application Gateway. If you need pure high-throughput Layer 4 distribution, use Azure Load Balancer. A common architecture combines these: Front Door at the edge handles global routing and edge W-A-F, Application Gateway within a region handles U-R-L routing and regional W-A-F, and an Internal Load Balancer distributes traffic between application tiers inside the V-Net.

To summarise. Azure Load Balancer is Layer 4, uses a five-tuple hash, and requires Standard S-K-U for zone redundancy and outbound rules. Use H-A Ports on an internal Load Balancer for N-V-A load balancing. Application Gateway is Layer 7, supports path-based and multi-site routing, S-S-L termination, and W-A-F — use W-A-F v2 S-K-U for built-in protection. Front Door provides global H-T-T-P load balancing with C-D-N and edge W-A-F. Traffic Manager provides D-N-S-based routing for any protocol with multiple routing methods including geographic and priority failover.

In the next topic, we will look at Azure D-N-S and Traffic Manager in more depth, covering private D-N-S zones, custom domain setup, and D-N-S-based routing strategies.
